If the consecutive integers from $50$ to $1$ were written as $$5049484746...,$$ what would be the $67^{\text{th}}$ digit to be written?
inference:
The number of digits in each integer is $2$.

So, the number of digits in $50$ consecutive integers is $2 \times 50 = 100$.

Therefore, the $67^{\text{th}}$ digit will be the $7^{\text{th}}$ digit of the $34^{\text{th}}$ integer.

The $34^{\text{th}}$ integer is $50 - 33 = 17$.

The $7^{\text{th}}$ digit of $17$ is $\boxed{7}$.
Final Answer: \boxed{$7$}. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth: The first $66$ digits are $33$ two-digit integers.  The first $33$ integers written are $50$ to $18$.  Thus the $67^{\text{th}}$ digit is the first digit of $17$, which is $\boxed{1}$.
